description:
From dia- (“through”) +‎ electric.
Learned 19th-century formation, coined by William Whewell (died 1866).

adjectives.description: dielectric (comparative more dielectric, superlative most dielectric)

entries.meaning: (physics) An electrically insulating or nonconducting material considered for its electric susceptibility, i.e. its property of polarization when exposed to an external electric field.
